	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f98333780561542><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=11&mid=98333780561542>RE: Grouping Tactics</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=11&mid=98333780561542#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=1471><span id=Sage>Cryselle</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>35 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Feb 28th 12:23 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.72]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Using the MOB's HP is only a good indicator of whether it is safe to nuke or not when you are in a group with a very limited number of people doing damage. In most groups, trying to use this method will have you either nuking later than need be, or aggroing too quickly. (Nuking later than need be is generally preferable, which is why people tend to suggest you wait until 3/4 or even 2/3. <br><br>The most important things to know for nuking is how much the nuke will aggro, how fast other classes aggro, and what you will do if you misjudged.<br><br>For the first, you need to know that Rangers build up aggro the quickest, then Warriors, then Bards, then SKs, then Paladins, then Monks, then Rogues of the melee classes. (This assumes that taunting classes are taunting, bards are combining song and weapons, and rogues are using evade) If you are in a group with the high end taunters, you can nuke more often than if you are in a group with a monk and a rogue.<br><br>Also be aware of special spells of other classes. Most importantly, Mez, Charm, and major debuffs all have a huge taunt, whereas landing an ice comet a half second after the chanter uses mem blur is a Bad Thing.<br><br>As for our spells... most of them are very straightforward, which makes controlling aggro fairly easy. More damage = more aggro. Only real time this doesn't apply is stuns, which have higher aggro than their damage, but wizards rarely are called upon to chain stun unless the opponent is low enough HP to be casting CH or Gate. This, however, is why moving from Ice Comet to Draught of Fire is a godsend to most wizards. It's a lot easier to control 2 600 damage nukes than one 1100 damage nuke.<br><br>A trick I've found for checking aggro after my first nuke is to sit down. If it turns on me when I take a seat, then it's too soon for another nuke. If I can safely sit on my butt for 5-10 seconds (giving time for the mob to finish being stunned from a bash and get to me, if it wants to) then I can nuke again. Concussion helps if I misjudge, before that you just have to take a beating for a few seconds. Even at high levels you can generally survive long enough for a tank with taunt to get it off you if you don't panic.<br><br><br>Cryselle Silverwynd<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
